# v0.1.1 Design Draft: Persistent Oxigraph Graph Authority

## Version intent

Make the v0.1 graph-authoritative architecture durable across process restarts.

v0.1 proved the Character Memory object model with embedded/in-memory Oxigraph.
v0.1.1 makes that authority persistent so Qdrant candidate recall cannot outlive the graph state required for provenance, lifecycle, correction, and retrieval safety.

## Why this comes before v0.2

v0.2 continuity features depend on durable graph state.
Relationship state, character signals, open loops, commitments, and reflection should not be built on an in-memory authority layer.

## Non-goals

- New memory concepts
- Claim/evidence/belief ontology
- Reflection scheduler
- Advanced retention governance
- Multimodal support
- True distributed transactions

## Deliverables

- Persistent graph store configuration
- Configurable in-memory vs persistent Oxigraph mode
- Restart-safe graph authority tests
- Qdrant/Oxigraph reconciliation diagnostics
- Retrieval validation gates for graph-authoritative currentness/provenance/retention
- Documentation for local persistent graph setup

## Acceptance criteria

- Objects survive graph store restart.
- Links survive graph store restart.
- Suppression/supersession/currentness survive restart.
- Retrieval after restart excludes suppressed and superseded records.
- Qdrant candidates whose graph objects are missing are rejected.
- Reconciliation can report vector-only and graph-only drift.
- In-memory mode remains available for deterministic tests.

## Design constraints

- Qdrant remains candidate recall only.
- Oxigraph remains authoritative for object existence, links, provenance, lifecycle, currentness, and correction.
- Stable object IDs and deterministic graph IRIs remain unchanged.
- Partial persistence may create repairable degraded state, but not behavior-influencing ungrounded memory.
